                \n {"practice":"6","code":"DM-3","subCode":"c)","explanation":"The requirement mandates a systematic process to identify all affected products or versions when a security-related issue is discovered, ensuring comprehensive vulnerability management.","context":"This is critical in ICS environments where vulnerabilities in one product may propagate across interconnected systems, leading to widespread security risks.","challenges":["Lack of centralized product inventory: Without a complete inventory, identifying all affected products is difficult. Example: A vulnerability in a PLC firmware may go unnoticed in legacy systems.","Version fragmentation: Multiple versions of the same product may be deployed, complicating tracking. Example: Different plant sites using varying versions of an HMI.","Third-party dependencies: Security issues in third-party components may not be immediately visible. Example: A vulnerable library used across multiple ICS products.","Legacy system compatibility: Older systems may not support modern vulnerability scanning tools. Example: A 20-year-old SCADA system lacking patch management capabilities.","Supply chain opacity: Vendors may not disclose component origins, hindering issue tracing. Example: A compromised OEM device affecting multiple vendors' products."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Maintain a comprehensive asset inventory with version tracking. Example: Using automated tools like Claroty or Tenable.ot to map ICS assets.","url":"https://claroty.com/industrial-cybersecurity-best-practices","url_description":"Claroty's guide on asset inventory for ICS security, relevant for DM-3(c)."},{"description":"Implement SBOM (Software Bill of Materials) for all products. Example: Using SPDX format to track components in PLC firmware.","url":"https://www.ntia.gov/SBOM","url_description":"NTIA's SBOM resources, critical for component-level vulnerability tracking."},{"description":"Establish vendor communication protocols for vuln